t-contract.md:47-58] | Medium | Low | Idea-level rewrite; copying the axis table or stamp is substantial textual reuse and requires MIT notice. |\n50: | 14 | named anti-pattern report shape | `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/audit-report-template.md` | SKIP | Do not replace the shipped finding schema with Hallmark's shorter tell/where/severity/fix form. Shipped observation, evidence label, user impact, owner, and accessibility coverage are stronger. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/anti-patterns.md:403-418] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/audit-contract.md:106-137] | None | None | Inferior/redundant; no reuse. |\n51: | 15 | visual bans: gates 1, 2, 7, 22, 23, 37, 38a, 54 | `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/procedures/ai-slop-check.md` | SKIP | Do not import these as universal automatic failures. Keep them as contextual hypotheses only when repetition, accessibility, register mismatch, or brief mismatch establishes harm. The shipped procedure already requires that posture. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/slop-test.md:28-36] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/slop-test.md:61-68] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/slop-test.md:94-100] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/slop-test.md:178-182] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/procedures/ai-slop-check.md:33-39] | Avoids false positives | None | Inappropriate as blanket contract; no reuse. |\n52: | 16 | Hallmark stamps, project log, catalog, and studied-DNA gates 20-21, 32, 57 | `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/procedures/ai-slop-check.md` | SKIP | Do not add Hallmark-private provenance stamps, `.hallmark/log.json`, macrostructure catalog enforcement, or conversation-scoped studied-DNA state to generic `sk-design` audit. Use shipped target evidence and optional non-authoritative corpus comparison instead. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/slop-test.md:56-65] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/slop-test.md:79-84] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/slop-test.md:184-188] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:176-189] | Avoids foreign state coupling | None | Product-specific and inappropriate; no reuse. |\n53: | 17 | candidate registry additions above | `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual-testing-playbook/slop-hardening/ai-fingerprint-tells.md` | ADAPT | Add clean/positive fixtures and exact-one-tell expectations for every promoted registry row; preserve source-backed `confirmed` versus screenshot-only `inferred` labels. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual-testing-playbook/slop-hardening/ai-fingerprint-tells.md:36-55] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/ai-fingerprint-registry.json:1-92] | High | Medium | Native sk-design test extension; no Hallmark text needs copying. |\n54: \n55: ## Copying And MIT Boundary\n56: \n57: No direct `COPY` candidate is recommended in this iteration. The useful Hallmark material can be implemented more coherently as independently worded, evidence-aware checks under the shipped P0-P3 and owner-routing contract. Copying the six-axis table, detailed multi-part gate prose, implementation recipes, or substantial anti-pattern entries would be copying substantial expression and should carry Hallmark's copyright and MIT permission notice; independently restating the underlying idea and integrating it into native terminology is idea-level adaptation. Hallmark's checked-in license requires the notice in copies or substantial portions. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/LICENSE:5-13]\n58: \n59: ## Questions Answered\n60: \n61: - **Answered:** Why do Hallmark sources say both 57 and 58? The checklist has 57 as its highest integer plus distinct gate `38a`, so the current total is 58; README's 57 is stale. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/slop-test.md:98-106] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/README.md:13-13]\n62: - **Answered:** Which Hallmark audit concepts are absent or weaker? Structural page/chrome fingerprints, fabricated content, fake chrome, input geometry, and several responsive edge-case probes are more granular than the reviewed shipped audit assets. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/slop-test.md:128-188] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/ai-fingerprint-registry.json:1-92] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/anti-patterns-production.md:101-117]\n63: - **Answered:** Which Hallmark concepts should not be imported? Direct severity semantics, universal taste bans, Hallmark stamps/log/catalog state, and replacement of the shipped five-dimension audit contract are redundant or inappropriate. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/verbs/audit.md:3-16] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/audit-contract.md:36-58] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/procedures/ai-slop-check.md:33-39]\n64: \n65: ## Questions Remaining\n66: \n67: - Which Hallmark interface/foundations structural systems improve generation-time direction without duplicating audit-time checks?\n68: - Which registry candidates survive fixture design without overlapping existing tells or creating broad false positives?\n69: - Where should a future Hallmark MIT notice live if implementation chooses substantial textual reuse despite the idea-level recommendation?\n70: \n71: ## Ruled Out\n72: \n73: - **Ruled out:** Treating README's 57 as evidence that one gate was deleted. The current list explicitly says 58 and contains integer gates 1-57 plus `38a`. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/slop-test.md:1-3] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/slop-test.md:98-106]\n74: - **Ruled out:** Replacing shipped P0-P3 severity with Hallmark's critical/major/minor labels. The shipped severity is tied to user and release impact, while Hallmark's critical category includes style signatures that need not block a user task. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/anti-patterns.md:9-15] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/audit-contract.md:36-45]\n75: - **Ruled out:** Copying all 58 gates into `design-audit`. Several are Hallmark-runtime state checks, several duplicate shipped token/accessibility/hardening rules, and several universal bans conflict with the shipped hypothesis-and-register posture. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/slop-test.md:3-5] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/procedures/ai-slop-check.md:33-39]\n76: \n77: ## Dead Ends\n78: \n79: - The initial Hallmark brace glob returned no matches despite known files. Direct reads of the exact iteration-1 paths resolved the inventory without changing scope.\n80: - A one-to-one gate count against the nine-row registry is not meaningful: the registry intentionally contains model fingerprints, while many Hallmark gates belong to accessibility, responsive, theming, or Hallmark-private state. Comparison therefore used behavioral coverage rather than raw row parity. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/ai-fingerprint-registry.json:1-92] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:139-152]\n81: \n82: ## Assessment\n83: \n84: - **Status:** complete for iteration 2's bounded focus.\n85: - **findingsCount:** 17 candidate rows.\n86: - **newInfoRatio:** 0.82.\n87: - **Novelty justification:** The iteration resolved the count discrepancy, established the shipped audit contract as the severity/evidence authority, and isolated seventeen path-specific adoption or rejection decisions that were absent from the inventory-only first pass.\n88: - **Convergence:** Do not stop. The configured max-iterations policy requires ten iterations; this result should feed the next structural generation comparison.\n89: \n90: ## Recommended Next Focus\n91: \n92: Compare Hallmark's macrostructure, component archetype, genre, theme, and redesign guidance against `design-interface` and `design-foundations`, separating audit-time detection from generation-time prevention.\n93: \n94: ## Sources Consulted\n95: \n96: - Hallmark `slop-test.md`, `anti-patterns.md`, `references/verbs/audit.md`, `SKILL.md`, `README.md`, and `LICENSE`. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/slop-test.md:1-192] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/anti-patterns.md:1-418] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/verbs/audit.md:1-25] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/SKILL.md:42-56]\n97: - Shipped audit mode, audit contract, AI-slop procedure, production reference, fingerprint catalog/registry/self-defect card, score rubric, and manual hardening scenarios. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:83-118] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/audit-contract.md:1-138] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/procedures/ai-slop-check.md:1-44] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/anti-patterns-production.md:1-127] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/ai-fingerprint-tells.md:1-156] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/ai-fingerprint-registry.json:1-92] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/anti-patterns-score-rubric.md:1-45] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/assets/ai-fingerprint-self-defect-card.md:1-51] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual-testing-playbook/slop-hardening/anti-slop-production-hardening.md:21-55] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/manual-testing-playbook/slop-hardening/ai-fingerprint-tells.md:20-70]\n\n(End of file - total 97 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"| 9 | gate 49 clickable text wrapping | `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/anti-patterns-production.md` | ADAPT | Add a rendered-width probe for wrapped primary affordance labels and classify by user impact, extending the existing long-text/translation checks. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/slop-test.md:160-166] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/anti-patterns-production.md:101-112] | High | Low | Idea-level rewrite; no MIT notice required. |\n| 10 | gates 50-52 intrinsic grids, long words, themed section heads | `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/anti-patterns-production.md` | ADAPT | Add three deterministic responsive probes: image-bearing `1fr` tracks without zero minimum, display text without emergency wrapping/zero min-w