{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784531513160,"sessionID":"ses_08202bafbffe7aMYl1BZMs5SAo","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_EZdldFwzsnys8Pn9MPdW8OZD","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/001-research/research/lineages/sol-opencode/deep-research-strategy.md","offset":1,"limit":130},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/001-research/research/lineages/sol-opencode/deep-research-strategy.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Deep Research Strategy: Hallmark to sk-design\n2: \n3: ## 2. TOPIC\n4: Study Hallmark as a design skill for AI coding assistants and produce a licensed, evidence-grounded reuse and learning matrix for surgical improvements to the shipped sk-design hub, its five mode packets, commands, audit checklists, design-reference/MD-generator pipeline, and styles corpus.\n5: \n6: <!-- ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n7: ## 3. KEY QUESTIONS (remaining)\n8: - [ ] What does Hallmark's license permit us to copy, adapt, and redistribute, and what attribution or notice obligations apply?\n9: - [ ] Which Hallmark assets map to sk-design interface, foundations, audit, md-generator/design-reference, and motion, and what concrete gaps exist in each target?\n10: - [ ] Which Hallmark slop gates, pre-emit critique heuristics, schemas, motion tokens, and design-DNA fields are absent or weaker in sk-design?\n11: - [ ] Is Hallmark's curated twenty-theme model a useful complement to sk-design's extracted styles corpus, and if so how should the two models coexist?\n12: - [ ] Which redesign, variant, brand-first, data-visualization, tactile, and image-hook roadmap ideas merit existing-mode adaptation, new capabilities, or rejection?\n13: \n14: <!-- /ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n15: \n16: ## 4. NON-GOALS\n17: - Do not implement or modify sk-design or Hallmark.\n18: - Do not replace sk-design wholesale or treat Hallmark as canon.\n19: - Do not infer copy rights beyond the checked-in license text.\n20: - Do not recommend generic design advice without naming a concrete sk-design target and evidence.\n21: \n22: ## 5. STOP CONDITIONS\n23: - Complete exactly 10 iterations because stopPolicy is max-iterations.\n24: - Synthesize only after all 10 iteration artifacts pass the route-proof and delta checks.\n25: - Treat early convergence as telemetry and broaden to an unreviewed asset family instead of stopping.\n26: \n27: <!-- ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n28: ## 6. ANSWERED QUESTIONS\n29: [None yet]\n30: \n31: <!-- /ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n32: \n33: <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: START -->\n34: <!-- ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n35: ## 7. WHAT WORKED\n36: - structural counting established exact corpus cardinality, while contract-level comparison separated selection authority from explanatory metadata. (iteration 7)\n37: \n38: <!-- /ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n39: \n40: <!-- ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n41: ## 8. WHAT FAILED\n42: - broad cardinality grep matched arbitrary extracted numeric content, so it could not establish inventory size. (iteration 7)\n43: \n44: <!-- /ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n45: \n46: <!-- ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n47: ## 9. EXHAUSTED APPROACHES (do not retry)\n48: ### **Copying the 21 macrostructures or 50 component archetypes as sk-design presets.** This conflicts with subject grounding and the no-reusable-preset guard. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/references/design-process/variation-diversity.md:111-116] -- BLOCKED (iteration 3, 1 attempts)\n49: - What was tried: **Copying the 21 macrostructures or 50 component archetypes as sk-design presets.** This conflicts with subject grounding and the no-reusable-preset guard. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/references/design-process/variation-diversity.md:111-116]\n50: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n51: - Do NOT retry: **Copying the 21 macrostructures or 50 component archetypes as sk-design presets.** This conflicts with subject grounding and the no-reusable-preset guard. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/references/design-process/variation-diversity.md:111-116]\n52: \n53: ### **Replacing foundations responsive guidance with fixed viewport recipes.** Existing foundations adapts across viewport, input, capability, and posture, which is the stronger abstraction. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/references/layout/adaptation-matrix.md:35-60] -- BLOCKED (iteration 3, 1 attempts)\n54: - What was tried: **Replacing foundations responsive guidance with fixed viewport recipes.** Existing foundations adapts across viewport, input, capability, and posture, which is the stronger abstraction. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/references/layout/adaptation-matrix.md:35-60]\n55: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n56: - Do NOT retry: **Replacing foundations responsive guidance with fixed viewport recipes.** Existing foundations adapts across viewport, input, capability, and posture, which is the stronger abstraction. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/references/layout/adaptation-matrix.md:35-60]\n57: \n58: ### **Ruled out:** Copying all 58 gates into `design-audit`. Several are Hallmark-runtime state checks, several duplicate shipped token/accessibility/hardening rules, and several universal bans conflict with the shipped hypothesis-and-register posture. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/slop-test.md:3-5] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/procedures/ai-slop-check.md:33-39] -- BLOCKED (iteration 2, 1 attempts)\n59: - What was tried: **Ruled out:** Copying all 58 gates into `design-audit`. Several are Hallmark-runtime state checks, several duplicate shipped token/accessibility/hardening rules, and several universal bans conflict with the shipped hypothesis-and-register posture. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/slop-test.md:3-5] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/procedures/ai-slop-check.md:33-39]\n60: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n61: - Do NOT retry: **Ruled out:** Copying all 58 gates into `design-audit`. Several are Hallmark-runtime state checks, several duplicate shipped token/accessibility/hardening rules, and several universal bans conflict with the shipped hypothesis-and-register posture. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/slop-test.md:3-5] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/procedures/ai-slop-check.md:33-39]\n62: \n63: ### **Ruled out:** Replacing shipped P0-P3 severity with Hallmark's critical/major/minor labels. The shipped severity is tied to user and release impact, while Hallmark's critical category includes style signatures that need not block a user task. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/anti-patterns.md:9-15] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/audit-contract.md:36-45] -- BLOCKED (iteration 2, 1 attempts)\n64: - What was tried: **Ruled out:** Replacing shipped P0-P3 severity with Hallmark's critical/major/minor labels. The shipped severity is tied to user and release impact, while Hallmark's critical category includes style signatures that need not block a user task. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/anti-patterns.md:9-15] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/audit-contract.md:36-45]\n65: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n66: - Do NOT retry: **Ruled out:** Replacing shipped P0-P3 severity with Hallmark's critical/major/minor labels. The shipped severity is tied to user and release impact, while Hallmark's critical category includes style signatures that need not block a user task. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/anti-patterns.md:9-15] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/references/audit-contract.md:36-45]\n67: \n68: ### **Ruled out:** Treating Hallmark's portable `design.md` as evidence that shipped `sk-design` lacks a design-reference pipeline. The shipped md-generator already has a measured extract-write-validate backend and explicit v3 schema. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:230-259] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/backend/scripts/schema-v3.ts:90-120] -- BLOCKED (iteration 1, 1 attempts)\n69: - What was tried: **Ruled out:** Treating Hallmark's portable `design.md` as evidence that shipped `sk-design` lacks a design-reference pipeline. The shipped md-generator already has a measured extract-write-validate backend and explicit v3 schema. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:230-259] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/backend/scripts/schema-v3.ts:90-120]\n70: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n71: - Do NOT retry: **Ruled out:** Treating Hallmark's portable `design.md` as evidence that shipped `sk-design` lacks a design-reference pipeline. The shipped md-generator already has a measured extract-write-validate backend and explicit v3 schema. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:230-259] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/backend/scripts/schema-v3.ts:90-120]\n72: \n73: ### **Ruled out:** Treating README.md's \"Use it, fork it, ship it\" sentence as the complete licensing contract. The actual MIT text adds a notice-preservation condition. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/README.md:110-112] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/LICENSE:12-13] -- BLOCKED (iteration 1, 1 attempts)\n74: - What was tried: **Ruled out:** Treating README.md's \"Use it, fork it, ship it\" sentence as the complete licensing contract. The actual MIT text adds a notice-preservation condition. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/README.md:110-112] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/LICENSE:12-13]\n75: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n76: - Do NOT retry: **Ruled out:** Treating README.md's \"Use it, fork it, ship it\" sentence as the complete licensing contract. The actual MIT text adds a notice-preservation condition. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/README.md:110-112] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/LICENSE:12-13]\n77: \n78: ### **Ruled out:** Treating README's 57 as evidence that one gate was deleted. The current list explicitly says 58 and contains integer gates 1-57 plus `38a`. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/slop-test.md:1-3] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/slop-test.md:98-106] -- BLOCKED (iteration 2, 1 attempts)\n79: - What was tried: **Ruled out:** Treating README's 57 as evidence that one gate was deleted. The current list explicitly says 58 and contains integer gates 1-57 plus `38a`. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/slop-test.md:1-3] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/slop-test.md:98-106]\n80: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n81: - Do NOT retry: **Ruled out:** Treating README's 57 as evidence that one gate was deleted. The current list explicitly says 58 and contains integer gates 1-57 plus `38a`. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/slop-test.md:1-3] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/external/hallmark/skills/hallmark/references/slop-test.md:98-106]\n82: \n83: ### **Separate redesign mode or command.** Existing interface triggers, redesign lane, and preserve/overhaul intake already provide the equivalent; the observed gap is multi-surface coherence inside the existing reference. [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/interface/design.md:55-59] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/references/design-process/redesign-intake.md:35-70] -- BLOCKED (iteration 3, 1 attempts)\n84: - What was tried: **Separate redesign mode or command.** Existing interface triggers, redesign lane, and preserve/overhaul intake already provide the equivalent; the observed gap is multi-surface coherence inside the existing reference. [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/interface/design.md:55-59] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/references/design-process/redesign-intake.md:35-70]\n85: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n86: - Do NOT retry: **Separate redesign mode or command.** Existing interface triggers, redesign lane, and preserve/overhaul intake already provide the equivalent; the observed gap is multi-surface coherence inside the existing reference. [SOURCE: .opencode/commands/interface/design.md:55-59] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/references/design-process/redesign-intake.md:35-70]\n87: \n88: ### **Separate variant command.** Existing `directions`, seed-of-thought, wireframe, and variation-set contracts already own it, and the procedure cards explicitly remain private. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/procedures/variation-set.md:19-27] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/procedures/wireframe-exploration.md:19-27] -- BLOCKED (iteration 3, 1 attempts)\n89: - What was tried: **Separate variant command.** Existing `directions`, seed-of-thought, wireframe, and variation-set contracts already own it, and the procedure cards explicitly remain private. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/procedures/variation-set.md:19-27] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/procedures/wireframe-exploration.md:19-27]\n90: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n91: - Do NOT retry: **Separate variant command.** Existing `directions`, seed-of-thought, wireframe, and variation-set contracts already own it, and the procedure cards explicitly remain private. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/procedures/variation-set.md:19-27] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/procedures/wireframe-exploration.md:19-27]\n92: \n93: ### `preview-examples.md` demonstrates Hallmark's own presets; abstracting those examples into a sk-design catalog would revive an exhausted direction. -- BLOCKED (iteration 9, 1 attempts)\n94: - What was tried: `preview-examples.md` demonstrates Hallmark's own presets; abstracting those examples into a sk-design catalog would revive an exhausted direction.\n95: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n96: - Do NOT retry: `preview-examples.md` demonstrates Hallmark's own presets; abstracting those examples into a sk-design catalog would revive an exhausted direction.\n97: \n98: ### A `tactile` theme, dial, preset, or trend mandate. -- BLOCKED (iteration 9, 1 attempts)\n99: - What was tried: A `tactile` theme, dial, preset, or trend mandate.\n100: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n101: - Do NOT retry: A `tactile` theme, dial, preset, or trend mandate.\n102: \n103: ### A brace glob for the named Hallmark files returned no matches, repeating the repository glob limitation noted in iteration 2. Exact paths from iteration 1's inventory were readable and supplied complete evidence; no scope expansion was needed. -- BLOCKED (iteration 3, 1 attempts)\n104: - What was tried: A brace glob for the named Hallmark files returned no matches, repeating the repository glob limitation noted in iteration 2. Exact paths from iteration 1's inventory were readable and supplied complete evidence; no scope expansion was needed.\n105: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n106: - Do NOT retry: A brace glob for the named Hallmark files returned no matches, repeating the repository glob limitation noted in iteration 2. Exact paths from iteration 1's inventory were readable and supplied complete evidence; no scope expansion was needed.\n107: \n108: ### A cookbook of copied HTML/CSS would create a parallel implementation library and reusable defaults; only the abstract decision-card shape survives. -- BLOCKED (iteration 8, 1 attempts)\n109: - What was tried: A cookbook of copied HTML/CSS would create a parallel implementation library and reusable defaults; only the abstract decision-card shape survives.\n110: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n111: - Do NOT retry: A cookbook of copied HTML/CSS would create a parallel implementation library and reusable defaults; only the abstract decision-card shape survives.\n112: \n113: ### A Nanobanana-specific core hook, prompt-hash cache, or generated-image provider lock. -- BLOCKED (iteration 9, 1 attempts)\n114: - What was tried: A Nanobanana-specific core hook, prompt-hash cache, or generated-image provider lock.\n115: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n116: - Do NOT retry: A Nanobanana-specific core hook, prompt-hash cache, or generated-image provider lock.\n117: \n118: ### A new live-preview MCP server or automated render-to-acceptance loop. -- BLOCKED (iteration 9, 1 attempts)\n119: - What was tried: A new live-preview MCP server or automated render-to-acceptance loop.\n120: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n121: - Do NOT retry: A new live-preview MCP server or automated render-to-acceptance loop.\n122: \n123: ### A new multi-page extraction relationship type; `DesignBoundary` already represents the measured relationship. -- BLOCKED (iteration 8, 1 attempts)\n124: - What was tried: A new multi-page extraction relationship type; `DesignBoundary` already represents the measured relationship.\n125: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n126: - Do NOT retry: A new multi-page extraction relationship type; `DesignBoundary` already represents the measured relationship.\n127: \n128: ### A new theme-motion, microinteraction, interaction-state, or reduced-motion command; `/interface:motion` and existing mode assets already own the jobs. -- BLOCKED (iteration 5, 1 attempts)\n129: - What was tried: A new theme-motion, microinteraction, interaction-state, or reduced-motion command; `/interface:motion` and existing mode assets already own the jobs.\n130: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n\n(Showing lines 1-130 of 568. Use offset=131 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Deep Research Strategy: Hallmark to sk-design\n\n## 2. TOPIC\nStudy Hallmark as a design skill for AI coding assistants and produce a licensed, evidence-grounded reuse and learning matrix for surgical improvements to the shipped sk-design hub, its five mode packets, commands, audit checklists, design-reference/MD-generator pipeline, and styles corpus.\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n## 3. KEY QUESTIONS (remaining)\n- [ ] What does Hallmark's license permit us to copy, adapt, and redistribute, and what attribution or notice obligations apply?\n- [ ] Which Hallmark assets map to sk-design interface, foundations, audit, md-generator/design-reference, and motion, and what concrete gaps exist in each target?\n- [ ] Which Hallmark slop gates, pre-emit critique heuristics, schemas, motion tokens, and design-DNA fields are absent or weaker in sk-design?\n- [ ] Is Hallmark's curated twenty-theme model a useful complement to sk-design's extracted styles corpus, and if so how should the two models coexist?\n- [ ] Which redesign, variant, brand-first, data-visualization, tactile, and image-hook roadmap ideas merit existing-mode adaptation, new capabilities, or rejection?\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n\n## 4. NON-GOALS\n- Do not implement or modify sk-design or Hallmark.\n- Do not replace sk-design wholesale or treat Hallmark as canon.\n- Do not infer copy rights beyond the checked-in license text.\n- Do not recommend generic design advice without naming a concrete sk-design target and evidence.","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/014-hallmark-design-skill-research/001-research/research/lineages/sol-opencode/deep-research-strategy.md","text":"# Deep Research Strategy: Hallmark to sk-design\n\n## 2. TOPIC\nStudy Hallmark as a design skill for AI coding assistants and produce a licensed, evidence-grounded reuse and learning matrix for surgical improvements to the shipped sk-design hub, its five mode packets, commands, audit checklists, design-reference/MD-generator pipeline, and styles corpus.\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n## 3. KEY QUESTIONS (remaining)\n- [ ] What does Hallmark's license permit us to copy, adapt, and redistribute, and what attribution or notice obligations apply?\n- [ ] Which Hallmark assets map to sk-design interface, foundations, audit, md-generator/design-reference, and motion, and what concrete gaps exist in each target?\n- [ ] Which Hallmark slop gates, pre-emit critique heuristics, schemas, motion tokens, and design-DNA fields are absent or weaker in sk-design?\n- [ ] Is Hallmark's curated twenty-theme model a useful complement to sk-design's extracted styles corpus, and if so how should the two models coexist?\n- [ ] Which redesign, variant, brand-first, data-visualization, tactile, and image-hook roadmap ideas merit existing-mode adaptation, new capabilities, or rejection?\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n\n## 4. NON-GOALS\n- Do not implement or modify sk-design or Hallmark.\n- Do not replace sk-design wholesale or treat Hallmark as canon.\n- Do not infer copy rights beyond the checked-in license text.\n- Do not recommend generic design advice without naming a concrete sk-design target and evidence.\n\n## 5. STOP CONDITIONS\n- Complete exactly 10 iterations because stopPolicy is max-iterations.\n- Synthesize only after all 10 iteration artifacts pass the route-proof and delta checks.\n- Treat early convergence as telemetry and broaden to an unreviewed asset family instead of stopping.\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n## 6. ANSWERED QUESTIONS\n[None yet]\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n\n<!-- MACHINE-OWNED: START -->\n<!-- ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n## 7. WHAT WORKED\n- structural counting established exact corpus cardinality, while contract-level comparison separated selection authority from explanatory metadata. (iteration 7)\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n## 8. WHAT FAILED\n- broad cardinality grep matched arbitrary extracted numeric content, so it could not establish inventory size. (iteration 7)\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n## 9. EXHAUSTED APPROACHES (do not retry)\n### **Copying the 21 macrostructures or 50 component archetypes as sk-design presets.** This conflicts with subject grounding and the no-reusable-preset guard. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/references/design-process/variation-diversity.md:111-116] -- BLOCKED (iteration 3, 1 attempts)\n- What was tried: **Copying the 21 macrostructures or 50 component archetypes as sk-design presets.** This conflicts with subject grounding and the no-reusable-preset guard. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/references/design-process/variation-diversity.md:111-116]\n- Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n- Do NOT retry: **Copying the 21 macrostructures or 50 component archetypes as sk-design presets.** This conflicts with subject grounding and the no-reusable-preset guard. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/references/design-process/variation-diversity.md:111-116]\n\n### **Replacing foundations responsive guidance with fixed viewport recipes.** Existing foundations adapts across viewport, input, capability, and posture, which is the stronger abstraction. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/references/layout/adaptation-matrix.md:35-60] -- BLOCKED (iteration 3, 1 attempts)\n- What was tried: **Replacing foundations responsive guidance with fixed viewport recipes.** Existing foundations adapts across viewport, input, capability, and posture, which is the stronger abstraction. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/references/layout/adaptation-matrix.md:35-60]\n- Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n- Do NOT retry: **Replacing foundations responsive guidance with fixed viewport recipes.** Existing foundations adapts across viewport, input, capability, and posture, which is the stronger abstraction. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/references/layout/adaptation-matrix.md:35-60]\n\n### **Ruled out:** Copying all 58 gates into `design-audit`. Several are Hallmark-runtime state checks, several duplicate shipped token/accessibility/hardening rules, and several universal bans conflict with the shipped hypothesis-and-register postu